Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the linguine.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} and half the garlic. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> TIP: Watch them like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Once cooked, transfer the toasted crumbs to a #bowl{} and set aside.

When boiling, add the @linguine{180%g} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Pop the (now empty) frying pan back onto a medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Add the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} to the pan and cook until blistered, ~{4-5%minutes}. With the back of a #spatula{}, press down onto the tomatoes so that they burst open.

Stir in the remaining garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Reduce the heat slightly then add the @creme fraiche{150%g}, @vegetable stock powder{1} and @water{75%ml}. Bring to the boil, simmer for ~{2%minutes}, then remove from the heat. Add the pasta to the sauce and toss together. Taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in another frying pan on medium-high heat. Season the @sea bass fillets{2} with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Once hot, carefully place your sea bass into the pan, skin-side down. Cook for ~{3-4%minutes} before turning over and cooking for ~{2-3%minutes} on the other side.

> TIP: To get crispy skin on the fish, don't move it around when it's cooking skin-side down.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

When ready, serve the creamy linguine in #bowls{}. Top with the sea bass and sprinkle the garlicky crumbs over. Enjoy!